    Vanilla Bayesian Coresets

    Function for implementing Bayesian Coresets with the Hilbert Frank Wolfe method

    get_coreset_frankwolfe.Rd

    This function implements Algorithm 2 and 3 described in the paper Automated Scalable Bayesian Inference via Hilbert Coresets for the case of logistic regression. It is a simplified version of the algorithm written in Python by the paper's first author, Trevor Campbell, which is available here. For obtaining the approximate posterior required in order to compute (approximate) sensitivities and norms it uses the function `LaplaceApproximation()` from the package `LaplacesDemon`.

    Usage

    get_coreset_frankwolfe(
  x,
  y,
  m = NA,
  num_projections = 500,
  seed = 1234,
  verbose = FALSE
)

    Arguments

    x

    a (n x d) covariate matrix.

    y

    a (n x 1) vector of -1, 1 observed data.

    m

    (optional) a scalar, indicating the maximum number of data points that will be included in the returned Bayesian coreset. If not specified, this value will be set to n/10 rounded down to the nearest integer.

    num_projections

    a scalar indicating the dimension of finite-dimensional approximation of log-likelihood to be used.

    seed

    (optional) a value to set the seed. Since the uniform coreset method is not deterministic, given all other function inputs remain the same, this value can be set to ensure that the same coreset is returned.

    verbose

    (optional) default is FALSE. If set to TRUE, status messages will be printed while the function runs.

    Value

    a list containing the following elements:

    • datapoints_selected - the indices for the data points selected to be part of the coreset.

    • weights - the computed weights for each point in the coreset.

    • xc - the feature matrix containing only the coreset data points.

    • yc - the reponse vector containing only the responses for the observations in the coreset.

    Examples

    # Using the defaults

## simulate binary data
data <- simulate_logit_data()
get_coreset_frankwolfe(data$x, data$y)
